05154nam a2200769Ia 9781503637238DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2023016821  a97815036372387 a10.1515/97815036372382doi  a(DE-B1597)666699  a(OCoLC)1376938258  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDS113.8.G4 4aDS113.8.G4b.A453 2024 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a305.3089924056940904223  aNQ 5750qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/128638:1 aAlianov-Rautenberg, Viola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Longer Ladies and Gentlemen :bGender and the German-Jewish Migration to Mandatory Palestine /cViola Alianov-Rautenberg. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Jewish History and C00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Migration, Gender, and Change -- t1 Liftmenschen in the Levant -- t2 We Are the West in the East -- t3 Capable Women and Men in Crisis? -- t4 How to Cook in Palestine? -- t5 Qualities That the Present Age Demands -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the sixty thousand German Jews who escaped Nazi Germany and found refuge in Mandatory Palestine between 1933 and 1940, migration meant radical changes: it transformed their professional and cultural lives and confronted them with a new language, climate, and society. Bridging German-Jewish and Israeli history, this book tells the story of German-Jewish migration to Mandatory Palestine/Eretz Israel as gender history. It argues that this migration was shaped and structured by gendered policies and ideologies and experienced by men and women in a gendered form—from the decision to immigrate and the anticipation of change, through the outcomes for family life, body, self-image, and sexuality. Immigration led to immediate transformations in allocations of tasks within the family, concepts of masculinity and femininity, and participation in the labor market and domestic life. Through a close examination of archival materials in German, English, and Hebrew, including administrative records, personal documents, newspapers, and oral history interviews conducted by the author, this book follows Jewish migrants along their journey from Germany and into the workplaces, living rooms, and kitchens of their new homeland, providing a new perspective on everyday life in Mandatory Palestine. Viola Alianov-Rautenberg's work illuminates key issues at the intersection of migration studies, German-Jewish studies, and Israeli history, demonstrating how the lens of gender enriches our understanding of social change, power, ethnicity, and nation-building.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJews, GermanzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolezPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aGender.  aGerman Jews.  aIsrael.  aJewish Gender History.  aJewish Migration History.  aMandate Palestine.  aMigration.  aNazi Germany.  aYishuv.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503637238?locatt=mode:legacy40uh